03961nam a22004575i 9780226820583DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226820583  a(DE-B1597)634872  a(OCoLC)1334887266  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aMUS0000002bisacsh1 aSchweig, Meredith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRenegade Rhymes :bRap Music, Narrative, and Knowledge in Taiwan /cMeredith Schweig. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b18 halftones, 4 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Studies in Ethnomusicology00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes on Romanization and Translation -- tList of Figures and Musical Examples -- tPrologue: First, the Rain -- tIntroduction: Tales of Taiwan -- tPART ONE Polyphonic Histories -- tChapter One It Depends on How You Define “Rap”... -- tChapter Two ...Because Others Might Define It Differently -- tPART TWO Narratives and Knowledge -- tChapter Three Masculinity Politics and Rap’s Fraternal Order -- tChapter Four Performing Musical Knowledge Work -- tChapter Five “We Are So Strong, We Are Writing History” -- tEpilogue: Then, the Sunflowers -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA close look at how Taiwanese musicians are using rap music as a creative way to explore and reconcile Taiwanese identity and history. Like many states emerging from oppressive political rule, Taiwan saw a cultural explosion in the late 1980s, when nearly four decades of martial law under the Chinese Nationalist Party ended. As members of a multicultural, multilingual society with a complex history of migration and colonization, Taiwanese people entered this moment of political transformation eager to tell their stories and grapple with their identities. In Renegade Rhymes, ethnomusicologist Meredith Schweig shows how rap music has become a powerful tool in the post-authoritarian period for both exploring and producing new knowledge about the ethnic, cultural, and political history of Taiwan. ​ Schweig draws on extensive ethnographic fieldwork, taking readers to concert venues, music video sets, scenes of protest, and more to show how early MCs from marginalized ethnic groups infused rap with important aspects of their own local languages, music, and narrative traditions. Aiming their critiques at the educational system and a neoliberal economy, new generations of rappers have used the art form to nurture associational bonds and rehearse rituals of democratic citizenship, making a new kind of sense out of their complicated present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aTaiwan, rap, hip-hop, narrative, post-authoritarian, ethnography, pedagogy, neoliberal, Kuomintang.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226820583423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226820583/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles